# Circuit AI Provider

Circuit is the ONLY active generative-AI provider. OpenAI is retired and must
not reappear as an active runtime provider path.

## Contract
- The attached Circuit notebook / sanitized cURL is the authoritative source of
  truth for the token request and the inference request/response shapes.
- The exact wire mapping lives in ONE file: `src/lib/circuit/contract.ts`.
  Confirm/adjust field names and response paths there against the notebook
  (`CIRCUIT_CONTRACT.txt`) — never scatter Circuit HTTP shapes across the
  codebase.
- The current contract defaults are PROVISIONAL and gated: until
  `CIRCUIT_CONTRACT_CONFIRMED=true`, the token manager and client return
  `CIRCUIT_CONTRACT_UNCONFIRMED` and make NO network request. Never remove this
  gate or let an unconfirmed/assumed payload run silently.
- Token flow is OAuth2 client-credentials (client id + secret → short-lived
  access token). The access token is in-memory runtime state only.

## Never
- Do not hard-code a Circuit endpoint or model name in TypeScript. Read
  `CIRCUIT_TOKEN_URL`, `CIRCUIT_INFERENCE_URL`, and `CIRCUIT_MODEL` from config.
- Do not require or send an App Key (`CIRCUIT_APP_KEY`) unless the CURRENT
  notebook cURL includes a required App Key field/header. Do not infer one from
  an old screenshot.
- Do not persist, log, hash, or partially display the client secret or access
  token; never return them in API JSON.
- Do not let Circuit override deterministic arithmetic, routing, evidence
  identity, account truth, delivery-target safety, deduplication, or audit.

## Always
- Every Circuit-generated material claim must cite supplied evidence IDs; reject
  evidence IDs, URLs, or people not present in the input bundle.
- Validate Circuit JSON with Zod; attempt one repair; then fall back to the
  deterministic path. A provider failure must never destroy the deterministic
  result.
- Resolve the active provider through `@/lib/ai-provider/registry`
  (`getActiveAiProvider`), not by reading env in components.
- Both application flows (Market + Buyer Intelligence and Signal-to-Action)
  share one token manager and one client.
